</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Replacement with a prosthetic heart valve (PHV) remains the definitive surgical procedure for management of severe cardiac valve disease. PHV dysfunction is uncommon but can be a life-threatening condition. The broad hemodynamic and pathophysiologic manifestations of PHV dysfunction are stenosis, regurgitation, and a stuck leaflet. Specific structural abnormalities that cause PHV dysfunction include prosthetic valve–patient mismatch, structural failure, valve calcification, dehiscence, paravalvular leak, infective endocarditis, abscess, pseudoaneurysm, abnormal connections, thrombus, hypoattenuating leaflet thickening, and pannus. Multiple imaging modalities are available for evaluating a PHV and its dysfunction. Transthoracic echocardiography is often the first-line imaging modality, with additional modalities such as transesophageal echocardiography, CT, MRI, cine fluoroscopy, and nuclear medicine used for further characterization and establishing a specific cause. The authors review PHVs and the role of imaging modalities in evaluation of PHV dysfunction and illustrate the imaging appearances of different complications.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2019</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180177">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180177">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig1.jpeg" height="1719" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Most common types of PHVs. Mechanical valves are of the bileaflet, monoleaflet, or caged-ball type. Bioprosthetic valves can be stented or stentless, and some can be placed transcutaneously.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig2.jpeg" height="1700" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Valvular stenosis in a patient who underwent the Ross procedure and had a pulmonary allograft. Sagittal balanced SSFP MR image shows stenosis of the pulmonary valve, with flow acceleration seen as a dark jet in the pulmonary artery (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig3.jpeg" height="1700" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Valvular regurgitation in a patient with levotransposition of the great arteries. Four-chamber balanced SSFP image shows a mechanical tricuspid valve (curved arrow) with backward spin dephasing in systole (straight arrow), indicative of valvular regurgitation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig4a.jpeg" height="1784" width="1567" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Normal measurements of valve mobility for a bileaflet mechanical aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Fluoroscopic images show normal opening <b>(a)</b> and closing <b>(b)</b> angles, which are measured as the angles between the two leaflets in the fully opened and closed positions, respectively. <b>(c, d)</b> CT images orthogonal to the valve show normal opening <b>(c)</b> and closing <b>(d)</b> angles; by convention, angles at CT are measured with a reference line parallel to the valve ring.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig4b.jpeg" height="1784" width="1785" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Normal measurements of valve mobility for a bileaflet mechanical aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Fluoroscopic images show normal opening <b>(a)</b> and closing <b>(b)</b> angles, which are measured as the angles between the two leaflets in the fully opened and closed positions, respectively. <b>(c, d)</b> CT images orthogonal to the valve show normal opening <b>(c)</b> and closing <b>(d)</b> angles; by convention, angles at CT are measured with a reference line parallel to the valve ring.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig4c.jpeg" height="1308" width="1681" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Normal measurements of valve mobility for a bileaflet mechanical aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Fluoroscopic images show normal opening <b>(a)</b> and closing <b>(b)</b> angles, which are measured as the angles between the two leaflets in the fully opened and closed positions, respectively. <b>(c, d)</b> CT images orthogonal to the valve show normal opening <b>(c)</b> and closing <b>(d)</b> angles; by convention, angles at CT are measured with a reference line parallel to the valve ring.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig4d.jpeg" height="1309" width="1679" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span>. Normal measurements of valve mobility for a bileaflet mechanical aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Fluoroscopic images show normal opening <b>(a)</b> and closing <b>(b)</b> angles, which are measured as the angles between the two leaflets in the fully opened and closed positions, respectively. <b>(c, d)</b> CT images orthogonal to the valve show normal opening <b>(c)</b> and closing <b>(d)</b> angles; by convention, angles at CT are measured with a reference line parallel to the valve ring.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig5a.jpeg" height="1086" width="1073" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Abnormal opening and closing angles in a 76-year-old woman with a dysfunctional mechanical mitral valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Initial CT images show normal opening <b>(a)</b> and closing <b>(b)</b> angles. <b>(c)</b> CT image 10 days later for reassessment of the valve after development of an elevated transvalvular gradient at echocardiography shows fixed position of the posterior leaflet, which has a low opening angle of 29°.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig5b.jpeg" height="1086" width="1313" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Abnormal opening and closing angles in a 76-year-old woman with a dysfunctional mechanical mitral valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Initial CT images show normal opening <b>(a)</b> and closing <b>(b)</b> angles. <b>(c)</b> CT image 10 days later for reassessment of the valve after development of an elevated transvalvular gradient at echocardiography shows fixed position of the posterior leaflet, which has a low opening angle of 29°.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig5c.jpeg" height="1086" width="1313" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Abnormal opening and closing angles in a 76-year-old woman with a dysfunctional mechanical mitral valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Initial CT images show normal opening <b>(a)</b> and closing <b>(b)</b> angles. <b>(c)</b> CT image 10 days later for reassessment of the valve after development of an elevated transvalvular gradient at echocardiography shows fixed position of the posterior leaflet, which has a low opening angle of 29°.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig6a.jpeg" height="1303" width="1538" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Stuck leaflet. <b>(a)</b> Drawing shows a mechanical aortic valve with a nonfunctioning posterior leaflet (arrow), as viewed from the left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a nonmobile anterior leaflet (arrow) of a mechanical mitral valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig6b.jpeg" height="1303" width="1405" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Stuck leaflet. <b>(a)</b> Drawing shows a mechanical aortic valve with a nonfunctioning posterior leaflet (arrow), as viewed from the left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a nonmobile anterior leaflet (arrow) of a mechanical mitral valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig7a.jpeg" height="1396" width="2104" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. PPM. <b>(a)</b> Drawing shows a bileaflet mechanical valve and a bioprosthetic valve in the open position. The effective orifice area (EOA) is highlighted in yellow. Note that this is smaller than the native valve size owing to the space occupied by the device component. <b>(b)</b> Doppler echocardiogram in a patient with a bioprosthetic aortic valve (Hancock 23 mm; Medtronic, Minneapolis, Minn) and PPM shows features of stenosis with short acceleration time and significantly elevated peak velocity. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in another patient shows prolapse of an aortic valve cusp (arrow) owing to undersizing of an aortic valve homograft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig7b.jpeg" height="1385" width="2053" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. PPM. <b>(a)</b> Drawing shows a bileaflet mechanical valve and a bioprosthetic valve in the open position. The effective orifice area (EOA) is highlighted in yellow. Note that this is smaller than the native valve size owing to the space occupied by the device component. <b>(b)</b> Doppler echocardiogram in a patient with a bioprosthetic aortic valve (Hancock 23 mm; Medtronic, Minneapolis, Minn) and PPM shows features of stenosis with short acceleration time and significantly elevated peak velocity. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in another patient shows prolapse of an aortic valve cusp (arrow) owing to undersizing of an aortic valve homograft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig7c.jpeg" height="1385" width="1602" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. PPM. <b>(a)</b> Drawing shows a bileaflet mechanical valve and a bioprosthetic valve in the open position. The effective orifice area (EOA) is highlighted in yellow. Note that this is smaller than the native valve size owing to the space occupied by the device component. <b>(b)</b> Doppler echocardiogram in a patient with a bioprosthetic aortic valve (Hancock 23 mm; Medtronic, Minneapolis, Minn) and PPM shows features of stenosis with short acceleration time and significantly elevated peak velocity. <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in another patient shows prolapse of an aortic valve cusp (arrow) owing to undersizing of an aortic valve homograft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig8.jpeg" height="2100" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Structural failure. Lateral chest radiograph shows migration of a bioprosthetic aortic valve (arrow) into the descending aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig9a.jpeg" height="1400" width="1397" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Dehiscence. <b>(a)</b> Drawing shows dehiscence of a bioprosthetic aortic valve as viewed from the aorta, with separation of the sewing ring from the aortic annulus (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Dehiscence of a bioprosthetic mitral valve in a 58-year-old woman with endocarditis. Three-chamber <b>(b)</b> and four-chamber <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a bioprosthetic mitral valve (black arrow in <b>c</b>) with an abnormal aortomitral angle of 61°—calculated from the mitral annular projection (red arrow in <b>b</b> orthogonal to the mitral valve prosthesis) and the long axis of the left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) (blue arrow in <b>b</b>)—a finding indicative of dehiscence. An adjacent pseudoaneurysm (white arrow) extends from the basal medial wall of the left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP image in another patient shows separation of the sewing ring of a bioprosthetic aortic valve (arrow) from the native annulus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig9b.jpeg" height="1036" width="1223" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Dehiscence. <b>(a)</b> Drawing shows dehiscence of a bioprosthetic aortic valve as viewed from the aorta, with separation of the sewing ring from the aortic annulus (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Dehiscence of a bioprosthetic mitral valve in a 58-year-old woman with endocarditis. Three-chamber <b>(b)</b> and four-chamber <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a bioprosthetic mitral valve (black arrow in <b>c</b>) with an abnormal aortomitral angle of 61°—calculated from the mitral annular projection (red arrow in <b>b</b> orthogonal to the mitral valve prosthesis) and the long axis of the left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) (blue arrow in <b>b</b>)—a finding indicative of dehiscence. An adjacent pseudoaneurysm (white arrow) extends from the basal medial wall of the left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP image in another patient shows separation of the sewing ring of a bioprosthetic aortic valve (arrow) from the native annulus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig9c.jpeg" height="1040" width="1164" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Dehiscence. <b>(a)</b> Drawing shows dehiscence of a bioprosthetic aortic valve as viewed from the aorta, with separation of the sewing ring from the aortic annulus (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Dehiscence of a bioprosthetic mitral valve in a 58-year-old woman with endocarditis. Three-chamber <b>(b)</b> and four-chamber <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a bioprosthetic mitral valve (black arrow in <b>c</b>) with an abnormal aortomitral angle of 61°—calculated from the mitral annular projection (red arrow in <b>b</b> orthogonal to the mitral valve prosthesis) and the long axis of the left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) (blue arrow in <b>b</b>)—a finding indicative of dehiscence. An adjacent pseudoaneurysm (white arrow) extends from the basal medial wall of the left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP image in another patient shows separation of the sewing ring of a bioprosthetic aortic valve (arrow) from the native annulus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig9d.jpeg" height="1036" width="1320" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Dehiscence. <b>(a)</b> Drawing shows dehiscence of a bioprosthetic aortic valve as viewed from the aorta, with separation of the sewing ring from the aortic annulus (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Dehiscence of a bioprosthetic mitral valve in a 58-year-old woman with endocarditis. Three-chamber <b>(b)</b> and four-chamber <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show a bioprosthetic mitral valve (black arrow in <b>c</b>) with an abnormal aortomitral angle of 61°—calculated from the mitral annular projection (red arrow in <b>b</b> orthogonal to the mitral valve prosthesis) and the long axis of the left ventricular outflow tract (LVOT) (blue arrow in <b>b</b>)—a finding indicative of dehiscence. An adjacent pseudoaneurysm (white arrow) extends from the basal medial wall of the left ventricle. <b>(d)</b> Coronal balanced SSFP image in another patient shows separation of the sewing ring of a bioprosthetic aortic valve (arrow) from the native annulus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig10a.jpeg" height="1446" width="1411" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. PVL. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the heart in cross section shows a PVL (arrow) adjacent to a mechanical aortic valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a severe regurgitant jet in the LVOT (straight arrow) adjacent to a mechanical aortic valve with heavy acoustic shadowing (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in the same patient shows a PVL (straight arrow) adjacent to the mechanical valve (curved arrow), indicating communication between the aortic root and LVOT. <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in another patient shows a PVL (arrow) adjacent to a mechanical mitral valve, with communication between the left atrium and left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig10b.jpeg" height="1446" width="1532" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. PVL. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the heart in cross section shows a PVL (arrow) adjacent to a mechanical aortic valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a severe regurgitant jet in the LVOT (straight arrow) adjacent to a mechanical aortic valve with heavy acoustic shadowing (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in the same patient shows a PVL (straight arrow) adjacent to the mechanical valve (curved arrow), indicating communication between the aortic root and LVOT. <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in another patient shows a PVL (arrow) adjacent to a mechanical mitral valve, with communication between the left atrium and left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig10c.jpeg" height="1382" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. PVL. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the heart in cross section shows a PVL (arrow) adjacent to a mechanical aortic valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a severe regurgitant jet in the LVOT (straight arrow) adjacent to a mechanical aortic valve with heavy acoustic shadowing (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in the same patient shows a PVL (straight arrow) adjacent to the mechanical valve (curved arrow), indicating communication between the aortic root and LVOT. <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in another patient shows a PVL (arrow) adjacent to a mechanical mitral valve, with communication between the left atrium and left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig10d.jpeg" height="1401" width="1472" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span>. PVL. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the heart in cross section shows a PVL (arrow) adjacent to a mechanical aortic valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a severe regurgitant jet in the LVOT (straight arrow) adjacent to a mechanical aortic valve with heavy acoustic shadowing (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in the same patient shows a PVL (straight arrow) adjacent to the mechanical valve (curved arrow), indicating communication between the aortic root and LVOT. <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image in another patient shows a PVL (arrow) adjacent to a mechanical mitral valve, with communication between the left atrium and left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig11a.jpeg" height="1713" width="2524" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Treatment of PVL. <b>(a)</b> Commonly employed closure devices for treatment of PVL. The designs range in size and shape; the procedural physician closely matches the shape of the PVL and of the device. <b>(b)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a bileaflet mechanical mitral valve (straight arrow) with an adjacent paravalvular regurgitant jet (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram in the same patient after placement of an occluder device (arrow) shows no paravalvular regurgitant jet. <b>(d, e)</b> Four-chamber <b>(d)</b> and short-axis valve-plane <b>(e)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images in a 50-year-old man show a large PVL (straight arrow) adjacent to a mechanical mitral valve. Several additional PVLs adjacent to the valve have been repaired, as evidenced by several Amplatzer occluder devices (curved arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig11b.jpeg" height="1265" width="1491" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Treatment of PVL. <b>(a)</b> Commonly employed closure devices for treatment of PVL. The designs range in size and shape; the procedural physician closely matches the shape of the PVL and of the device. <b>(b)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a bileaflet mechanical mitral valve (straight arrow) with an adjacent paravalvular regurgitant jet (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram in the same patient after placement of an occluder device (arrow) shows no paravalvular regurgitant jet. <b>(d, e)</b> Four-chamber <b>(d)</b> and short-axis valve-plane <b>(e)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images in a 50-year-old man show a large PVL (straight arrow) adjacent to a mechanical mitral valve. Several additional PVLs adjacent to the valve have been repaired, as evidenced by several Amplatzer occluder devices (curved arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig11c.jpeg" height="1265" width="1472" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Treatment of PVL. <b>(a)</b> Commonly employed closure devices for treatment of PVL. The designs range in size and shape; the procedural physician closely matches the shape of the PVL and of the device. <b>(b)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a bileaflet mechanical mitral valve (straight arrow) with an adjacent paravalvular regurgitant jet (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram in the same patient after placement of an occluder device (arrow) shows no paravalvular regurgitant jet. <b>(d, e)</b> Four-chamber <b>(d)</b> and short-axis valve-plane <b>(e)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images in a 50-year-old man show a large PVL (straight arrow) adjacent to a mechanical mitral valve. Several additional PVLs adjacent to the valve have been repaired, as evidenced by several Amplatzer occluder devices (curved arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig11d.jpeg" height="1255" width="1471" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span>. Treatment of PVL. <b>(a)</b> Commonly employed closure devices for treatment of PVL. The designs range in size and shape; the procedural physician closely matches the shape of the PVL and of the device. <b>(b)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a bileaflet mechanical mitral valve (straight arrow) with an adjacent paravalvular regurgitant jet (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram in the same patient after placement of an occluder device (arrow) shows no paravalvular regurgitant jet. <b>(d, e)</b> Four-chamber <b>(d)</b> and short-axis valve-plane <b>(e)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images in a 50-year-old man show a large PVL (straight arrow) adjacent to a mechanical mitral valve. Several additional PVLs adjacent to the valve have been repaired, as evidenced by several Amplatzer occluder devices (curved arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig11e.jpeg" height="1249" width="1472" aria-labelledby="fig11e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11e</span>. Treatment of PVL. <b>(a)</b> Commonly employed closure devices for treatment of PVL. The designs range in size and shape; the procedural physician closely matches the shape of the PVL and of the device. <b>(b)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram shows a bileaflet mechanical mitral valve (straight arrow) with an adjacent paravalvular regurgitant jet (curved arrow). <b>(c)</b> Transesophageal echocardiogram in the same patient after placement of an occluder device (arrow) shows no paravalvular regurgitant jet. <b>(d, e)</b> Four-chamber <b>(d)</b> and short-axis valve-plane <b>(e)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images in a 50-year-old man show a large PVL (straight arrow) adjacent to a mechanical mitral valve. Several additional PVLs adjacent to the valve have been repaired, as evidenced by several Amplatzer occluder devices (curved arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig11e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig12a.jpeg" height="1400" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Vegetations. <b>(a)</b> Drawing shows vegetations (arrow) in a bioprosthetic valve. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image in a patient with infective endocarditis shows vegetations (arrow) involving the leaflets of a bioprosthetic valve. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image in the same patient shows infective endocarditis and vegetations in cross section (arrows). (<a href="#fig12a">Fig 12b and 12c</a> courtesy of Paul Schoenhagen, MD, Cleveland Clinic, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig12b.jpeg" height="1241" width="1281" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Vegetations. <b>(a)</b> Drawing shows vegetations (arrow) in a bioprosthetic valve. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image in a patient with infective endocarditis shows vegetations (arrow) involving the leaflets of a bioprosthetic valve. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image in the same patient shows infective endocarditis and vegetations in cross section (arrows). (<a href="#fig12a">Fig 12b and 12c</a> courtesy of Paul Schoenhagen, MD, Cleveland Clinic, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig12c.jpeg" height="1241" width="1669" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Vegetations. <b>(a)</b> Drawing shows vegetations (arrow) in a bioprosthetic valve. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image in a patient with infective endocarditis shows vegetations (arrow) involving the leaflets of a bioprosthetic valve. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image in the same patient shows infective endocarditis and vegetations in cross section (arrows). (<a href="#fig12a">Fig 12b and 12c</a> courtesy of Paul Schoenhagen, MD, Cleveland Clinic, Cleveland, Ohio.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig13a.jpeg" height="1316" width="1244" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Vegetation in a 6-year-old boy with repaired tetralogy of Fallot who presented with fever after placement of a bioprosthetic pulmonary valve. <b>(a)</b> Axial black-blood image shows an irregular intermediate-signal-intensity mass (arrow) attached to the pulmonary valve. <b>(b)</b> Axial SSFP image shows the mass (arrow) attached to the pulmonary valve. <b>(c)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the mass (arrow), which is consistent with a vegetation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig13b.jpeg" height="1316" width="1118" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Vegetation in a 6-year-old boy with repaired tetralogy of Fallot who presented with fever after placement of a bioprosthetic pulmonary valve. <b>(a)</b> Axial black-blood image shows an irregular intermediate-signal-intensity mass (arrow) attached to the pulmonary valve. <b>(b)</b> Axial SSFP image shows the mass (arrow) attached to the pulmonary valve. <b>(c)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the mass (arrow), which is consistent with a vegetation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig13c.jpeg" height="1316" width="1336" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Vegetation in a 6-year-old boy with repaired tetralogy of Fallot who presented with fever after placement of a bioprosthetic pulmonary valve. <b>(a)</b> Axial black-blood image shows an irregular intermediate-signal-intensity mass (arrow) attached to the pulmonary valve. <b>(b)</b> Axial SSFP image shows the mass (arrow) attached to the pulmonary valve. <b>(c)</b> Delayed contrast-enhanced image shows heterogeneous enhancement of the mass (arrow), which is consistent with a vegetation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig14a.jpeg" height="1224" width="1223" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Aortic root abscess. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the heart in cross section shows a mechanical aortic valve with an aortic root abscess (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis valve-plane TEE image of a mechanical aortic valve shows a large aortic root abscess (arrow) adjacent to the valve. <b>(c, d)</b> Orthogonal <b>(c)</b> and valve-plane <b>(d)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show the soft-tissue–attenuation abscess (white arrow) in the aortic root adjacent to the bileaflet mechanical valve (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig14b.jpeg" height="1224" width="1741" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Aortic root abscess. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the heart in cross section shows a mechanical aortic valve with an aortic root abscess (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis valve-plane TEE image of a mechanical aortic valve shows a large aortic root abscess (arrow) adjacent to the valve. <b>(c, d)</b> Orthogonal <b>(c)</b> and valve-plane <b>(d)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show the soft-tissue–attenuation abscess (white arrow) in the aortic root adjacent to the bileaflet mechanical valve (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig14c.jpeg" height="1455" width="1455" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Aortic root abscess. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the heart in cross section shows a mechanical aortic valve with an aortic root abscess (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis valve-plane TEE image of a mechanical aortic valve shows a large aortic root abscess (arrow) adjacent to the valve. <b>(c, d)</b> Orthogonal <b>(c)</b> and valve-plane <b>(d)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show the soft-tissue–attenuation abscess (white arrow) in the aortic root adjacent to the bileaflet mechanical valve (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig14d.jpeg" height="1455" width="1491" aria-labelledby="fig14d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14d</span>. Aortic root abscess. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the heart in cross section shows a mechanical aortic valve with an aortic root abscess (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Short-axis valve-plane TEE image of a mechanical aortic valve shows a large aortic root abscess (arrow) adjacent to the valve. <b>(c, d)</b> Orthogonal <b>(c)</b> and valve-plane <b>(d)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show the soft-tissue–attenuation abscess (white arrow) in the aortic root adjacent to the bileaflet mechanical valve (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig14d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig15a.jpeg" height="1109" width="1593" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Abscess in a patient with a bioprosthetic aortic valve. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber balanced SSFP image shows soft-tissue thickening (arrow) in the aortic root adjacent to the bioprosthetic aortic valve. <b>(b)</b> Axial <sup>18</sup>F-fluorodeoxyglucose PET/CT image shows increased radiotracer activity in the soft tissue adjacent to the bioprosthesis (arrow), consistent with active infection and abscess formation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig15b.jpeg" height="1109" width="1656" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Abscess in a patient with a bioprosthetic aortic valve. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber balanced SSFP image shows soft-tissue thickening (arrow) in the aortic root adjacent to the bioprosthetic aortic valve. <b>(b)</b> Axial <sup>18</sup>F-fluorodeoxyglucose PET/CT image shows increased radiotracer activity in the soft tissue adjacent to the bioprosthesis (arrow), consistent with active infection and abscess formation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig16a.jpeg" height="1434" width="1399" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Pseudoaneurysm. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the heart in cross section shows a paravalvular pseudoaneurysm (arrow) adjacent to a mechanical aortic valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Horizontal long-axis TEE image in a patient with a mechanical mitral valve shows a large pseudoaneurysm (arrow) at the base of the left ventricle. <b>(c)</b> Color Doppler image shows the “yin-yang” sign (arrow) with bidirectional flow in the pseudoaneurysm. <b>(d)</b> Maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image in the valve plane shows several small pseudoaneurysms (curved arrows) and a larger slow-filling pseudoaneurysm (straight arrow) adjacent to the mechanical valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig16b.jpeg" height="1029" width="1377" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Pseudoaneurysm. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the heart in cross section shows a paravalvular pseudoaneurysm (arrow) adjacent to a mechanical aortic valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Horizontal long-axis TEE image in a patient with a mechanical mitral valve shows a large pseudoaneurysm (arrow) at the base of the left ventricle. <b>(c)</b> Color Doppler image shows the “yin-yang” sign (arrow) with bidirectional flow in the pseudoaneurysm. <b>(d)</b> Maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image in the valve plane shows several small pseudoaneurysms (curved arrows) and a larger slow-filling pseudoaneurysm (straight arrow) adjacent to the mechanical valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig16c.jpeg" height="1028" width="1250" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span>. Pseudoaneurysm. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the heart in cross section shows a paravalvular pseudoaneurysm (arrow) adjacent to a mechanical aortic valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Horizontal long-axis TEE image in a patient with a mechanical mitral valve shows a large pseudoaneurysm (arrow) at the base of the left ventricle. <b>(c)</b> Color Doppler image shows the “yin-yang” sign (arrow) with bidirectional flow in the pseudoaneurysm. <b>(d)</b> Maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image in the valve plane shows several small pseudoaneurysms (curved arrows) and a larger slow-filling pseudoaneurysm (straight arrow) adjacent to the mechanical valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig16d.jpeg" height="1028" width="1070" aria-labelledby="fig16d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16d</span>. Pseudoaneurysm. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of the heart in cross section shows a paravalvular pseudoaneurysm (arrow) adjacent to a mechanical aortic valve. <i>Ao</i> = aorta, <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>LV</i> = left ventricle. <b>(b)</b> Horizontal long-axis TEE image in a patient with a mechanical mitral valve shows a large pseudoaneurysm (arrow) at the base of the left ventricle. <b>(c)</b> Color Doppler image shows the “yin-yang” sign (arrow) with bidirectional flow in the pseudoaneurysm. <b>(d)</b> Maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image in the valve plane shows several small pseudoaneurysms (curved arrows) and a larger slow-filling pseudoaneurysm (straight arrow) adjacent to the mechanical valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig16d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig17a.jpeg" height="1118" width="1313" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Thrombosed pseudoaneurysm in a patient with a bioprosthetic aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Three-chamber contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> and volumetric 3D rendering <b>(b)</b> show a paravalvular pseudoaneurysm (straight white arrow) with partial thrombosis (curved arrow in <b>a</b>). The pseudoaneurysm exerts mass effect on the left coronary and circumflex arteries, with severe narrowing at the origin of the circumflex artery (black arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Short-axis delayed contrast-enhanced MR image shows the large pseudoaneurysm (curved arrow) outlined by a rim of enhancement (black arrows) with partial thrombosis (straight white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig17b.jpeg" height="1118" width="1173" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Thrombosed pseudoaneurysm in a patient with a bioprosthetic aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Three-chamber contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> and volumetric 3D rendering <b>(b)</b> show a paravalvular pseudoaneurysm (straight white arrow) with partial thrombosis (curved arrow in <b>a</b>). The pseudoaneurysm exerts mass effect on the left coronary and circumflex arteries, with severe narrowing at the origin of the circumflex artery (black arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Short-axis delayed contrast-enhanced MR image shows the large pseudoaneurysm (curved arrow) outlined by a rim of enhancement (black arrows) with partial thrombosis (straight white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig17c.jpeg" height="1118" width="1215" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span>. Thrombosed pseudoaneurysm in a patient with a bioprosthetic aortic valve. <b>(a, b)</b> Three-chamber contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> and volumetric 3D rendering <b>(b)</b> show a paravalvular pseudoaneurysm (straight white arrow) with partial thrombosis (curved arrow in <b>a</b>). The pseudoaneurysm exerts mass effect on the left coronary and circumflex arteries, with severe narrowing at the origin of the circumflex artery (black arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Short-axis delayed contrast-enhanced MR image shows the large pseudoaneurysm (curved arrow) outlined by a rim of enhancement (black arrows) with partial thrombosis (straight white arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig18.jpeg" height="1714" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Aortic–right atrial fistula in a patient with a mechanical aortic valve. Short-axis balanced SSFP image shows a jet (curved arrow) extending from the right coronary sinus to the right atrium <i>(RA)</i>, consistent with an aortic–right atrial fistula. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, straight arrow = mechanical aortic valve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig19.jpeg" height="1712" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. Left atrium to LVOT communication in a 63-year-old man with a mechanical mitral valve. Three-chamber CT image shows a fistulous communication (arrow) between the left atrium <i>(LA)</i> and LVOT. The fistula is secondary to a PVL adjacent to a mechanical mitral valve. <i>LV</i> = left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig20a.jpeg" height="1383" width="1474" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Gerbode defect. <b>(a)</b> Coronal oblique contrast-enhanced CT image shows a PVL (straight arrow) adjacent to a mechanical aortic valve. There is also a Gerbode defect with communication between the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> and right atrium <i>(RA)</i>; this is partially closed by a membranous septum (curved arrow). <i>Ao</i> = aorta. <b>(b)</b> Angiogram shows a catheter extending through the paravalvular aortic defect (straight arrow) and a jet of contrast material (curved arrow) at the site of the Gerbode defect.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig20b.jpeg" height="1383" width="1474" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Gerbode defect. <b>(a)</b> Coronal oblique contrast-enhanced CT image shows a PVL (straight arrow) adjacent to a mechanical aortic valve. There is also a Gerbode defect with communication between the left ventricle <i>(LV)</i> and right atrium <i>(RA)</i>; this is partially closed by a membranous septum (curved arrow). <i>Ao</i> = aorta. <b>(b)</b> Angiogram shows a catheter extending through the paravalvular aortic defect (straight arrow) and a jet of contrast material (curved arrow) at the site of the Gerbode defect.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig21a.jpeg" height="1356" width="1354" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. Thrombus. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of a bileaflet mechanical aortic valve as viewed from the aorta shows thrombus (arrow) on the aortic surface of the valve. <b>(b)</b> Valve-plane contrast-enhanced CT image shows abnormal low-attenuation soft tissue (arrows) surrounding and extending into a mechanical aortic valve, consistent with thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig21b.jpeg" height="1356" width="1593" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. Thrombus. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of a bileaflet mechanical aortic valve as viewed from the aorta shows thrombus (arrow) on the aortic surface of the valve. <b>(b)</b> Valve-plane contrast-enhanced CT image shows abnormal low-attenuation soft tissue (arrows) surrounding and extending into a mechanical aortic valve, consistent with thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig22a.jpeg" height="1245" width="1348" aria-labelledby="fig22a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span>. Pannus. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of a mechanical aortic valve as viewed from the ventricle shows exuberant growth of host tissue (arrow), consistent with pannus. <b>(b)</b> Echocardiogram in a 41-year-old woman with a bioprosthetic aortic valve shows thickened valve leaflets and pannus (straight arrow), causing severe aortic stenosis (curved arrow) with an elevated mean gradient (50 mm Hg). <b>(c, d)</b> Valve-plane image <b>(c)</b> and image orthogonal to the valve <b>(d)</b> from contrast-enhanced CT in a 55-year-old man show abnormal soft tissue (arrows) surrounding and extending into a bioprosthetic aortic valve. The attenuation of the soft tissue was 230 HU.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig22b.jpeg" height="1245" width="1794" aria-labelledby="fig22b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span>. Pannus. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of a mechanical aortic valve as viewed from the ventricle shows exuberant growth of host tissue (arrow), consistent with pannus. <b>(b)</b> Echocardiogram in a 41-year-old woman with a bioprosthetic aortic valve shows thickened valve leaflets and pannus (straight arrow), causing severe aortic stenosis (curved arrow) with an elevated mean gradient (50 mm Hg). <b>(c, d)</b> Valve-plane image <b>(c)</b> and image orthogonal to the valve <b>(d)</b> from contrast-enhanced CT in a 55-year-old man show abnormal soft tissue (arrows) surrounding and extending into a bioprosthetic aortic valve. The attenuation of the soft tissue was 230 HU.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig22c.jpeg" height="1436" width="1470" aria-labelledby="fig22c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22c</span>. Pannus. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of a mechanical aortic valve as viewed from the ventricle shows exuberant growth of host tissue (arrow), consistent with pannus. <b>(b)</b> Echocardiogram in a 41-year-old woman with a bioprosthetic aortic valve shows thickened valve leaflets and pannus (straight arrow), causing severe aortic stenosis (curved arrow) with an elevated mean gradient (50 mm Hg). <b>(c, d)</b> Valve-plane image <b>(c)</b> and image orthogonal to the valve <b>(d)</b> from contrast-enhanced CT in a 55-year-old man show abnormal soft tissue (arrows) surrounding and extending into a bioprosthetic aortic valve. The attenuation of the soft tissue was 230 HU.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig22c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig22d.jpeg" height="1436" width="1680" aria-labelledby="fig22d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22d</span>. Pannus. <b>(a)</b> Drawing of a mechanical aortic valve as viewed from the ventricle shows exuberant growth of host tissue (arrow), consistent with pannus. <b>(b)</b> Echocardiogram in a 41-year-old woman with a bioprosthetic aortic valve shows thickened valve leaflets and pannus (straight arrow), causing severe aortic stenosis (curved arrow) with an elevated mean gradient (50 mm Hg). <b>(c, d)</b> Valve-plane image <b>(c)</b> and image orthogonal to the valve <b>(d)</b> from contrast-enhanced CT in a 55-year-old man show abnormal soft tissue (arrows) surrounding and extending into a bioprosthetic aortic valve. The attenuation of the soft tissue was 230 HU.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig22d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180177/asset/images/large/rg.2019180177.fig23.jpeg" height="1784" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span>. Aortic dissection in a patient with a bioprosthetic aortic valve. Coronal maximum intensity projection (MIP) contrast-enhanced CT image shows an aortic dissection flap (arrow) involving the proximal ascending aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180177&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Dunning J, Gao H, Chambers J, et al. Aortic valve surgery: marked increases in volume and significant decreases in mechanical valve use—an analysis of 41,227 patients over 5 years from the Society for Cardiothoracic Surgery in Great Britain and Ireland national database. <em>J Thorac Cardiovasc Surg</em> 2011;142(4):776–782.e3.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jtcvs.2011.04.048">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21924147/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Aortic+valve+surgery%3A+marked+increases+in+volume+and+significant+decreases+in+mechanical+valve+use%E2%80%94an+analysis+of+41%2C227+patients+over+5+years+from+the+Society+for+Cardiothoracic+Surgery+in+Great+Britain+and+Ireland+national+database&amp;author=J+Dunning&amp;author=H+Gao&amp;author=J+Chambers&amp;publication_year=2011&amp;journal=J+Thorac+Cardiovasc+Surg&amp;pages=776-782.e3&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.jtcvs.2011.04.048&amp;pmid=21924147">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="